The Prague Stock Exchange finished with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
<0xC4><0x8C>EZ’s share transactions reached approximately half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of trading Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday’s fall when it fell to about 6%.
The decline this time is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
Also here is the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives that refused to support the stabilization plan of the secretary of the financial sector.
Fall in shares in Asia
Shares of the Asian Stock Exchanges experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, although over the course of the day the index finally attenuated some of the losses.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Stock Exchange’s index throughout its financial day stood at nearly four percent, though it later attenuated its losses by reducing the decline by nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movements of Chinese shares in the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the index secretary, fell to 3.6 percent.
“The planned rescue actions in the U.S. are unsafe and this affects the financial market around the world,” said Hong Kong Currency Bureau Chief Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, that is, without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong’s interest rates are at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should reconvene as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that the falls will be felt in other countries.
The Bloody Bath of American Stocks
On Monday, the American Assembly of Representatives rejected the aid plan to the financial system to which $700 billion (almost 12 billion crowns) should be devoted.
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloody dip and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell to nearly seven percent, a similar volume drop last recorded in 1987.
The index dropped before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the proposal of the assembly did not go ahead, the index began to fall freely.
Congress withdraws: U.S. government could inject $700 billion into banking
The highest representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed on a pact in broad terms of financial aid to the American financial system.
The vote will take place early next week.
U.S. lawmakers caused a rift in talks about approving the bailout plan in its form of aid to the U.S. financial system with the amount of 700 billion dollars (about 12 billion kronor).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen need to fine-tune some details of the contract before they can make the final form of the law public and get it voted on.
The financial system assistance plan will be discussed at the Assembly of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Services Committee and the Assembly Bank, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could be held in the Senate not before Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the bailout plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
Then, however, "disenchantment" will be achieved thanks to the complex mechanisms whose market support will also reach in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made a great progress.
We have resolved our conflicting views on how the package of measures for market stabilization should be," Democrat Nancy Pelosi<0xC3><0xA1> told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still be held on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met Sunday night with Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give a final shape to the government fund.
This should buy from financial corporations the unsold mortgage assets that lead financial firms to heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are about to close the agreement on the plan, which will work and must also be effective in the market.
It is still necessary to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we are already in it," Paulson said.
A Sign for Asian Business
The global financial crisis has a strong impact on the rapidly declining stock market.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are doing everything possible for Congress to definitively pass a deal on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors in the face of the Asian financial market as these are the ones that are in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday’s trade.
However, for now, there is nothing clear with certainty about when the two chambers of the American Congress will vote and, not even, if they will not stagnate at the last moment with some problem.
Lawmakers believe it will be approved in the coming days.
The law, however, will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion must be available as soon as possible, as President George Bush requested.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it has the impression that the program does not fulfill its function, which would be another $100 billion and, later, the last $350 billion.
Bush appreciated the progress of the meetings
On the other hand, the president can veto this decision but Congress can override his veto by a majority vote.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was to gain financial resources for the repurchase of bad mortgage securities whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to finish paying their mortgages.
“We’ve worked everything.
The House of Representatives would have to be prepared to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the talks.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush is pleased with Saturday’s progress and appreciates “the commitment of both sides to stabilizing our financial market and protecting our economy.”
Limitation of the armored contract
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, head of the negotiators, said lawmakers decided on the responsibility of the program's money for protecting taxpayers' taxes from their losses, a easing close to the planned financial plan.
The new law must also limit so-called armored contracts for directors of the participating companies of the program, and create a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This would have to be directed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on it, and we’ve made a big breakthrough toward a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also has to help homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree to new mortgage payments it buys in order to lower the monthly burdens of installment payments from debtors and enable them to stay with their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but rather difficult.
“And that’s why it’s not known with what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for the distribution of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week, for the server iHNed.cz.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not so relevant, according to Marek.
"Much more important is that, already this week, Congressmen agree on their support and give him their good-bye as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to get that approval is, at the moment, the most important thing," Marek insisted.
Armed struggle: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost all mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
Which seems clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Still, there are enough reasons for man to acquire only the breeder.
The choice depends practically on the way of its use and the requirement of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for him to acquire the most modern records to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album on it.
On the other hand, this type of music products such as LPs no longer come out, and in terms of their quality there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues music are crammed onto your shelves, you’re probably dreaming, at least, of this type of record.
This is the same with the music that is on the way, that is, the music compressed, simplified - the music in MP3.
And here there are categories of price and quality.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as well as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try out the market helmets of twenty crowns.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also decides the duration of the battery
Some of the best players get a lot more than just playing music and even that which not even most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Faced with the most basic functions such as dialing, sending messages, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera and even get to navigate.
And when we consider the Smartphone and the PDAs will also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a small miracle since no refrigerator knows how to make a grill and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobile phones also brings us disadvantages.
The more features you use on your phone, the sooner the display indicator will light up asking to be recharged.
And playing music is one of the greatest energy tragedies.
There are few mobile phones that can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most of them much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) clearly perform better.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap mobile phones will not play for more than two hours.
If in addition to this, on top of constantly calling still get, for more safety, a charger for work - this is also valid for the most expensive devices.
With the MP3 player this problem will not have, because even the worst ones can withstand at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on mobile.
Unfortunately, only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, in addition, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly on the memory card but only on some reader units without reduction can the small memory cards that are used on mobiles be connected.
In players, with some exception (iPod), no special software is required.
Simply fill the device with music through the computer's USB.
Most mobile phones and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to the user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (river, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a particular equipment is interested in the resistance of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to music as a background and you will listen to it every day only for a while, as on the tram, then it is enough with any mobile that you play.
This is what virtually any mobile device can achieve.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or the player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and almost all the music that comes to it will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The minuses include the AAC format (the format used by Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
Simply through the mobile internet visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy yourself a song or album.
This service could in itself be a weighty argument for acquiring a mobile for music.
Unfortunately, the offer from the operators is miserable and the majority is limited only to the fleeting success issues of the radios.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a cell phone on top of them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you’ll find the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, hands-free ones.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has virtually every mobile even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobiles with music will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns can already acquire a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the absence of a classic headphone jack.
The best, even when it comes to the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input. for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing more than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to the previous cassettes or also to the turntables is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the Internet with the mobile phone and, consequently, huge account for data loss.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot to change the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card will reach two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are usually equipped only with a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive have a memory of 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1100 crowns.
If you consider yourself among the most demanding music lovers, get your hands on the most specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of a single player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles from the walkman line have almost identical use as that of an independent MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, over four thousand crowns, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand most arria brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
It's probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not gonna be long before we get there.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>TU), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming rates is likely to come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>TU), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, has already expressed that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classical operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in prices to which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market, similar voices were heard both here and there.
It has been shown that there is room for this type of operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look for examples too far away.
In February this year we informed you about the premiere of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, it is enough for them to have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, are often countered with the offer of more adjusted services.
So, for example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half of cheap compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial goal group.
This operator is directed specifically to man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and who he can trust,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works with this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether similar concept like that of Poland could hook up in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be some virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokesman for the financial group Penta.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of business customers.
“We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have been able to move forward in the meetings," said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they flash better times.
It seems that, according to unofficial information, the first official operator would probably have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesman for Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, in exceptional compliance with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
“On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At the moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting the own requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of the distribution of costs and infrastructure.
We consider it to be the greatest contribution from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a drop in prices and thereby a drop in profits.
So why facilitate entry into competition?
When traders want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>TU was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is attested by the public information available on the <0xC4><0x8C>TU website.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds: “Furthermore, it was not long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As for the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean great requirements for him and, above all, for his services."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile phone operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
So far no agreement has been closed as the supply of potential interested parties was rather not interesting enough for the classical operators,” added Kristian Chalupa, of the Department of Foreign Affairs of the UOHS.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that they should note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the drop in prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure as to the proper functioning of the market media and the fall in prices do not fall within the interest of the OHIM.
The really dramatically shocking thing in all this is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is a work of chance and of a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility in their actions in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation about the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is clearly an analysis of relevant markets developed by the <0xC4><0x8C>TU according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of the commercial tender a single market.
In this type of market of course none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly in a similar way.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with the operators there are many similar impediments.
Charge of responsibility in the <0xC4><0x8C>TU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the OHS is washing its hands in all this matter.
We have met with him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently introduced for the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>TU’s competition in the field of commercial tenders that was not carried out, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
Representatives of UOHS should know this perfectly, but it is obvious that their interests lie elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when no one's looking
At the same time, unobtrusively something like a pseudo-virtual operator still works that in the Czech mobile networks already exist a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services which, however, only a part are public.
Usually these are companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases like the ones you cite were discovered, you could talk about a breach in the contract conditions that could translate into the end of collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> answered the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned that they can reach thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get a negligible profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so many percent of customers.
They also have to accept that their phone’s SIM card is not in their name so they can’t absolutely dispose of it as a normal carrier customer.”
This is exactly what should seem to the <0xC4><0x8C>TU at least strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile operators surround their eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator’s entry?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has enough competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in practically all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this intrusion.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases did they defend the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to create the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority all this happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of the attributions in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market is likely to start moving again.
If one of the operators lets a virtual mobile operator in, it will be difficult for the OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
