The MHD of Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the history of the Prague Transport Company is written the date when the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased right now by almost one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from January 1, 2009) and simultaneously load it onto their chip card at the transport company’s info centers and stations at the Metro, Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, N<0xC3><0xA1>dra<0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD> Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Roztyly, Let<0xC5><0x88>aby, Raty<0xC5><0x88>any, and Raty<0xC5><0x88>any.
The bonds can be bought from yesterday on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about ticket booths at subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
“In these places, there is a ready-made staffed window available to passengers that helps those interested with online shopping and also with recharging the voucher purchased on their card,” said project spokesman Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>.
