Talking in Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not talking about those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they are asleep.
The first time it happens, you may get scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somnilochia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (making yourself sleepy) or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be that way.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or overexcitement.
However, it is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (crying, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him a way out.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stressor).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who find it hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the sleepy nights appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very anxious during several episodes, you should consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not usual), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him to sound out information.
You will get nothing, because being asleep is not conscious as to organize your thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say, so be very careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
