Free Review - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world’s largest goldsmith company attempted a six-million-euro defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate”.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation persecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance; the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the mine’s almost bottomless pockets.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will stifle the opposition as well as scare anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before public opinion that he would have had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by rattling.
It was enough for the miner to open her books, her files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a "public" debate by disregarding his views?
According to the Vice-President, it seems that this word designates only highly paid lawyers and not all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the mine’s brutal manner.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes of argument, and not within the framework of what many people perceive as a stalking-bitch (pursuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a request with respect to the authors of Noir Canada urging them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on the freedom of university search and truth, essential for all democratic societies.
He denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under pain of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s excessive persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he does not want to have a transparent debate.
It’s a loss for the university world, but also for the public debate in Canada, and it’s time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
