Psychology of Overlays: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auctioneers are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study, which appeared in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction and meanwhile the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined by means of the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI).
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the auto-reward mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 in prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the members of the group even lost that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, checking the neurologists hypothesis, the members of the group that played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
For those until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
In the world some five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E through food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and with body humors (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves by vaccine against A and B viruses, against C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after eating the infected food, manifested by a poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and on the whites of the eyes jaundice, excrement becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last even two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of the disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of the infected do not know that he is sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, it is very important early recognition, systematic medical control.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory monitoring as well, it is worth consulting with your family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so you can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain – reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scan technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from different departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis occurred as follows; they fixed a shimmering instrument on the patient’s left hand, which applied electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a 17th-century work by Sassoferrato and the 15th-century Lady of the Arminian by Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary show would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a calming effect.
The patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt “safe” as “protected” people, “they calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts.”
When they looked at the religious picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
“We should find a portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases does change our personality,” Wright added.
After these formidable results, only one question remains: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On his tenth birthday, Google can claim: he can be found both in people’s pocket and in the sky above his head; he knows where they spent their vacation, what doctors they visit and what is of interest to them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwellian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to gather as much personal data as possible about its users, and this is necessary to meet the original goals of Google’s founders: “We gather in one system all the information in the world!”
According to the leader of Google, the company, even after ten years of work that turned the world around, is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to process all the information.
To the question of what is going to happen in five years Schmidt answered thus: I would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What to do tomorrow?" or "What would be the best job for me?" - however, the software will not be able to answer questions seemingly so simple as long as there is not enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that the search keywords, IP addresses and the pages where they went when the search ended are accurately stored during their browsing on the Web.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can re-visit what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - on this same logic will be based the Recommendations, on which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences defined above and stored.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? – ask those users who are concerned about seeing the information monopoly of Google.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, longing for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a fact already confirmed that not only retain, but in justified cases also cede to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most debated example of recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google gave the Brazilian government information from its website, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
Instead, internet users who care about people’s rights in May were relieved when the company, together with the EFF, the electronic rights advocacy organization, successfully demonstrated before the court that it was right in its dispute with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google will not be forced, by any of the points of the constitution, to request FBI to supply any kind of information.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to get its pretext to strengthen the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without getting the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is quite contradictory opinion about Google: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their private life is harmed when they start using Google services, and they rebel against it as against the multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "vanguard corporation", not so to its rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the world, no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open source and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks accurately see the very problematic relationship between people’s rights and the Internet that came about precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the available communication channels, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Shanghai, and can even join them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then these can be included in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, you can also have a blog, in which the most recent photos are automatically stored on Flick.
We can know numerous cases from which it turns out that for example the bride, seeing the flow of photographs of the next morning of ordinary friends, finds out with whom she spent the night before her fraudulent boyfriend or can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the direction of the company: one thing is for sure, the definition of complete reva life.
A person's "online" life is what she shows of herself - this is the definition that lies behind the behavior of youth today.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least pretends to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do so (starting with, for example, the Scroogle that uses Google’s search engine, but leaves no footprints).
There are many people who don’t want to sign up on collective pages to avoid being able to find them, but they can replace Google’s “online” apps, from text-writing software to image-reading and news-reading apps with alternative versions that don’t connect with giant servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible on us.
Public opinion almost openly expects the day Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of 156 billion dollars is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca-Cola (110 billion dollars), the advertising surfaces of AdWords/AdSense threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while the services that are introduced more and more quickly cause Microsoft not only severe headaches.
Critical observers, however, will find the alarming contradictions too: for example, the top management flatly rejected the employee protest after doubling the price of the company's childcare, considered too expensive the unlimited number of feeding employees, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to the pressure of the Chinese government and the company's good news.
One of the internal regulations of the company says that they will not announce any new service in advance, but that only when it was already ready to operate, which if it is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to stir up the world: while some believe that the project of scanning and archive of books and magazines from Google will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be sued by the courts.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will provide a good raw material for science fiction writers, the Scroogled, novel by the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in an Orwellian way that future, in which a man only of Google's data can be described alarmingly well.
