The intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop technologies to avoid collisions, if not mimicking existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the beekeepers.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C robotic car steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
The compound eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, the engineers used the laser length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by rotating the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to dodge obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be performed at an opening and closing of the eyes.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car rotational movement and acceleration in addition to braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and higher in energy density, which means they have a longer service life than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, let alone the storage capacity.
This apparatus in every second only has to process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabytes or megabytes are needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge obstacles, which Nissan estimates will be able to incorporate into mass-produced models within 10 years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles existing in his way.
