Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices, the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 percent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimal extent, by 0.1 percent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to the 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry, there was a price increase between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent a significant weight within domestic trade, there was an increase of 0.3 percent in August, primarily due to the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally, prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supply exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while prices in the energy sector and intermediate sectors did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increases occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
There was a decline of 6.8 percent in consumer goods and 1.4 percent in investment goods.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 percent against the euro and 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
