The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 million bailout plan put in place by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and this, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
The New York Times confirmed yesterday that the ongoing crisis is disarming the Republican party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, supportive of federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, strong in the South and especially in the South.
The soul, in fact, has become prepotent with the vote of the one who spoke at the beginning.
This is just one example of the mutations, of the great mutations, that the ongoing economic earthquake announces: not only in the United States but in the entire West and not only here.
Both in the United States and in Europe for a long time the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of incubation phenomena that with the new climate solidify and come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary reactivation, of the dual state-sovereignty category in relation to a type of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking institutions – financial institutions that have, yes, strong financial relations with the outside world, but above all, the balance sheets of families living in a single country and in a single state are much more compromised.
The one that immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulty and protests of those people and those families who, on the other hand, are voters.
The crisis appears economically worldwide but is politically and exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems substantially out of the question or has little to say: the crucial test is the European Union which, as always, is divided between different interests and different state strategies, fails to decide any common policy.
It is from the government of each state that everyone expects an intervention, rescue and reactivation plans, new rules and above all the grant of funds: from the moment you arrive at the court is only the state that has the economic resources and the mass of financial resources to remedy things.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of incalculable value, values in certain circumstances in which no market and no organization can probably ever dispose of to the same extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the nation-state is in perfect harmony, with the greatest importance provided that the new development of the economy tends to attribute it to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the network of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to dominate the world, we realized that our future will instead have to do more and more with the immaterial things like water, crops and oil.
All things, you see, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are equally united in an absolute way in a circumscribed space, a territory.
So whoever finds himself sovereign certainly has many more letters than he who is not, and who has the misfortune of living in a post without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty that but foreshadows a fracture.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics and Leadership.
In this sense, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand the objective awareness of the need for leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, of an economic nature relieved inadequate with many dark areas.
And together something deeper and in a certain unsettling sense: a discredit, an intolerance, an inadequate image, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class of the Western countries in increasing numbers.
It seems to advance more and more, in various places of the population, the conviction that before their actions are the same as those of the hitherto booming social elites, the same way of feeling and being, their culture in the comprehensive exception of the term, to have made the time itself and to be stranger to the opinions of the majority.
