Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic rooms
Historical movie theaters close favoring the Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the big Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom a piece of place was shared and so much emotion", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury in Cannes, which told the poetry of a cinema in a way lost and the nostalgia for cinema that time to live.
The figures given by Anec, the main association of merchants, are clear: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and most of the rooms in the main cities are to be paid for: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for his disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new meticone cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, “it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala either in the historic center or on the periphery.
Among the planned rules there are fiscal facilitation measures in favor of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna’s example by putting other measures in place.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of meticons, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that for me was always important: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Cinema Paradise", which I had already thought of for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
