When the energy is born from the waves, the great ones come down to the stage.
It is an exterminated deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is being discovered now by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources that greats like Chevron look at.
The possibility of gathering energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s along with the first oil crisis, investigations intensified.
When the price of oil was low, in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now that environmental cases and the new oil increase give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated for 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of sea waves.
This would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And there would also be currents and tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an implant in Northern Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years away from betting on marine energy are always more and among these companies who have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technology,” a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question is about obtaining permission from the U.S. Energy Commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It’s a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the U.S. continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to make new drilling.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts talk about a technology still at the beginning, because marine energy has no doubt that it has a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts such as those of the Portuguese or Scots are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of wells joined together.
The force of the waves, which causes the buoys to move up and down becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure rotates a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast via submarine cables.
For now there are four such implants in development, waiting only for federal approval, apart from energy, could serve for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and parking lot, using underwater turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of the water when there are tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electric Power, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
While it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is above all about the tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others that are approaching the coast, have invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and an investment of 35 million is planned for 2009.
